DOC: nodeName="#document"
   ELEM: nodeName="fscode"
      TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue=[WS]
      ELEM: nodeName="title"
         TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="FSCode Formatting"
      TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue=[WS]
      ELEM: nodeName="toc"
            ATTR: nodeName="align" nodeValue="right"
               TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="right"
            ATTR: nodeName="float" nodeValue="yes"
               TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="yes"
      TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue=[WS]
      ELEM: nodeName="h1"
         TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="Tags"
      TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue=[WS]
      ELEM: nodeName="i"
         TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="Tags"
      TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue=" are how you specify text formatting in FSCode-enabled contexts.  FSCode is an HTML-like markup that supports more tags, more styles, and more features.  It also supports some "
      ELEM: nodeName="i"
         TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="macros"
      TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue=" which can automate a large amount of formatting and organizational typesetting work.  For instance, the table of contents for this page was automatically generated by a macro.

FSCode bears more similarity to typesetting software such as TeX or WikiSyntax.  What you type is interpreted to generate another kind of document which will display more advanced features.  You would use FSCode to write a document, and then later (or concurrently) tweak the output to adjust the display.  This ensures that all the formatting throughout the document is consistent.  If you are using FSCode as part of a web site then you probably have no control over the display - FSCode will still allow you a massive degree of flexibility in how you author content while keeping it aesthetically coordinated with the rest of the site.

"
      ELEM: nodeName="i"
         TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="Anatomy of a Tag"
      TEXT: nodeName="#text" nodeValue="

All tags have several things in common.  Firstly, they are all began with a less-than character (<).  They all have a name, and they all close with a greater-than character (>).  Tags that are unrecognized are ignored and will appear in the final product without any textual differences.  If you want to "escape" a tag (instruct FSCode to ignore it) then you should use the HTML character instructions &lt; for the less-than character < and &gt; for the greater-than character >.

Most tags also require a closing tag.  These closing tag uses a forward-slash (/) before the tag name, and is otherwise identical to any other tag.

A few example tags are given:

"
